1. Making figure with pyplot¶

In [265]:
# 1st method
fig = plt.figure() # Create a figure
ax = fig.add_subplot() # Adds some axes
plt.show()
In [266]:
# 2nd method
fig = plt.figure() # Create a figure
ax = fig.add_axes([1,1,1,1])
plt.plot(x,y)
plt.show()
In [267]:
# 3rd method (RECOMMENDED)
fig,ax = plt.subplots() # Create a figure
ax.plot(x,[100,250,300,450,700])
plt.show()

Matplotlib example workflow¶

In [268]:
# 0. Import matplotlib
%matplotlib inline
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from random import randint

# 1. Prepare the data
x=[randint(1,10) for x in range(0,10)]
y=[y1*10 for y1 in x]

# 2. Setup plot
fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,10)) # (width,height)

# 3. Plot the data
ax.plot(sorted(x),sorted(y))
plt.show()

# 4. Customize plot
ax.set(title="Simple Plot",xlabel="x-axis",ylabel="y-axis")

# 5. Save and Show
fig.savefig("images/simple-plot.png")

Two options for subplots¶

In [277]:
# Subplot option 1
fig, ((ax1,ax2),(ax3,ax4)) = plt.subplots(nrows=2,ncols=2,figsize=(10,5))

# Plot to each ax
ax1.plot(x,x**2)
ax2.scatter(np.random.random(10),np.random.random(10))
ax3.bar(nut_butter_prices.keys(),nut_butter_prices.values())
ax4.hist(x)
plt.show()
In [278]:
# Subplot option 2
fig,ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2,ncols=2,figsize=(10,5))

# Plot to each ax
ax[0,0].plot(x,x**2)
ax[0,1].scatter(np.random.random(10),np.random.random(10))
ax[1,0].bar(nut_butter_prices.keys(),nut_butter_prices.values())
ax[1,1].hist(x)
plt.show()

Which one to use? (Pyplot or matplotlib OO method)¶

  • When plotting something quickly, pyplot
  • When plotting something more advance, OO method

fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))

# Customize the plot
ax.set(title="Heart disease and Cholesterol level",xlabel="Age",ylabel="Chol")
ax.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(),title="Target")

# Add a horizontal line
ax.axhline(y=over_50["chol"].mean(),linestyle="--")

In [309]:
# Subplot of chol,age,thalach
fig, (ax1,ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows=2,ncols=1,figsize=(10,10),sharex=True)

scatter = ax1.scatter(x=over_50["age"],y=over_50["chol"],c=over_50["target"])
ax1.set(title="Heart disease and Cholesterol level",ylabel="chol")
ax1.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(),title="Target")
ax1.axhline(y=over_50["chol"].mean(),linestyle="--")

scatter = ax2.scatter(x=over_50["age"],y=over_50["thalach"],c=over_50["target"])
ax2.set(title="Heart disease and Max Heart rate",xlabel="age",ylabel="Max Heart Rage")
ax2.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(),title="target")
ax2.axhline(y=over_50["thalach"].mean(),linestyle="--")

# Add a title to the fig
fig.suptitle("Heart Disease Analysis",fontsize=16,fontweight="bold")
plt.show()

# Subplot of chol,age,thalach
fig, (ax1,ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows=2,ncols=1,figsize=(10,10))

scatter = ax1.scatter(x=over_50["age"],y=over_50["chol"],c=over_50["target"],cmap="winter")
ax1.set(title="Heart disease and Cholesterol level",xlabel="age",ylabel="chol")
ax1.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(),title="Target")
ax1.axhline(y=over_50["chol"].mean(),linestyle="--")
ax1.set_xlim([50,80])

scatter = ax2.scatter(x=over_50["age"],y=over_50["thalach"],c=over_50["target"],cmap="winter")
ax2.set(title="Heart disease and Max Heart rate",xlabel="age",ylabel="Max Heart Rage")
ax2.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(),title="target")
ax2.axhline(y=over_50["thalach"].mean(),linestyle="--")
ax2.set_xlim([50,80])
ax2.set_ylim([60,200])

# Add a title to the fig
fig.suptitle("Heart Disease Analysis",fontsize=16,fontweight="bold")
